  				<a href="http://kitchenography.typepad.com"><span class="alias">Julie</span></a>
  				<span>on May 11, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2061"><p>Lucky for mom and for me, I&#8217;m a December baby; I get whatever I want and she&#8217;s happy to oblige.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve never seen this rhubarb crisp before, mom. Have you been holding out on me? You know how fond I am of foods in the <a href="http://www.rhubarbinfo.com/rhubarb-poison.html#TOC82">poisonous</a> deadly nightshade family.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Leland</span></span>
  				<span>on May 11, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2062"><p>Thanks, Ivonne and Julie&#8212;I actually think it was overbaked a little bit; you can see from the photo that the rhubarb had basically turned to puree. That darn oven of mine is so unreliable, but I&#8217;ll be getting a new one soon.</p>
<p>Leland, now that the Ubers come for dinner every week I get a lot more free rhubarb; you wouldn&#8217;t believe how much they have in their back yard; it&#8217;s a rhubarb jungle back there! This is a really good recipe, though, and could be adapted for other fruits&#8212;also scaled down for smaller quantities.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Mommy</span></span>
  				<span>on May 11, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2063"><p>I have some rhubarb in the fridge, and a crisp was just what I was planning on doing with it. I am going to try your melted butter tip-it makes sense, though it never occured to me. You are indeed lucky to have friends who grow rhubarb!</p>
<p>I was wondering how the Watkins compares with the Penzey&#8217;s vanilla, which I love? They make a double-strength one too. Have you tried it?</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<a href="http://http;//lindystoast.com"><span class="alias">lindy</span></a>
  				<span>on May 11, 2006</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-2064"><p>Lindy, I&#8217;ve never actually tried the Penzey&#8217;s double strength vanilla, but I think the Watkin&#8217;s is much better than Neilson-Massey&#8217;s, which is generally held to be the gold standard and the one we used to sell at the <strong>Kitchen Wizard</strong>.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s the <a href="http://www.chefdecuisine.com/all_fruit/rhubarb/RHUBARB_CRISP.asp">recipe</a> I followed if you want to see the original; I had increased the proportions because I was serving a larger crowd. I added the vanilla to the topping, and used whole wheat flour throughout. Let me know how it turns out.</p></div>
